    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-09-04T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-09-04T06:00:00-05:00" n="612"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d612">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.00111 <hi rend="superscript">Lic. Wolf,
                        Rudolf/51</hi>/97: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-09-04T12:00:00+01:00"
                            >September 4, 1937—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received September 4—8:27
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1249. Reference Embassy’s telegram No. 1174, August 8[<hi rend="italic">18</hi>],
                    7 p.m. According to the press, on the night of August 29 there occurred an
                    explosion followed by fire in one of the hangars at the Airdrome Toussus, Paris,
                    in which some of these planes were being kept. The explosion was apparently
                    caused by chemicals placed there with a <pb facs="0611" n="599" xml:id="pg_599"
                    /> time fuse. An investigation is still taking place. One plane was practically
                    completely destroyed.</p>
                <p>The press further reports that on September 2 three of these planes obtained
                    permission from the Ministry of Air to leave the field and fly to Toulouse being
                    piloted by French pilots. A news despatch from Toulouse this morning states that
                    the planes have not yet arrived at Toulouse and no word has been heard of them,
                    the general assumption being that they have flown to Spain. Despatch
                        follows.<note n="73" xml:id="d612fn73">Not found in Department files.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bullitt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
